answers.body_markdown:
Right now you are trying to use an [Array initializer](https://docs.oracle.com/javase/specs/jls/se8/html/jls-10.html#jls-10.6), which is trying to create the `String` array with one element, the `int`, which is throwing the error. To do the size you must do:

    private String[] movieTitles = new String[MAXIMUM_RECORDS];

Which will create a `String` array with a size of `MAXIMUM_RECORDS`. And similarly with your other `Array`s:

````
private int[] movieIDs = new int[MAXIMUM_RECORDS];
private double[] moviePrices = new double[MAXIMUM_RECORDS];
````

For further information on initializing and creating `Array`&#39;s, please refer to the [Java tutorials](https://docs.oracle.com/javase/tutorial/java/nutsandbolts/arrays.html)

That is because your `Array` initialization is incorrect. There are three ways to declare `array` in java. If you want to create an `array` with specific size and define the values later you have to like this : 

```java
int[] myIntegerArray = new int[size_in_integer];
```
Or if you want to initialize it with values you can do it like this :

```java
int[] myIntArray = {1, 2, 3};
//OR
int[] myIntArray = new int[]{1, 2, 3};
```
Declaration procedure is same for primitive types and classes. For example in case of `String` you can initialize like this :

```java
String[] stringArray = new String[3];
String[] stringArray = {&quot;a&quot;, &quot;b&quot;, &quot;c&quot;};
String[] stringArray = new String[]{&quot;a&quot;, &quot;b&quot;, &quot;c&quot;};
```

